title: Background runners cannot be hosted and recovered in Herdr
---
Clawq cannot currently run a Codex or Claude background task inside a persistent Herdr agent terminal, even though Herdr exposes non-interactive lifecycle commands for agent start/list/get/read/send/wait/attach and pane close. As a result, queued GitHub work cannot use Herdr as the inspectable, recoverable execution host on subscriber PCs.

Add a Herdr adapter to the session-host interface from B768. Use herdr agent start with an explicit cwd and argv, store the returned/stable terminal or agent identity, map read/send/wait/attach/cancel operations to Herdr's structured CLI, and recover state after a Clawq daemon restart. Prefer argv-based execution and literal send operations; never construct a shell command from issue text or prompts.

Acceptance:
- A background task can select host=herdr while runner remains auto/codex/claude.
- Clawq can read progress, send a follow-up, wait for idle/done, cancel, and surface an attach command.
- Restart recovery distinguishes live, completed, missing, and stale Herdr terminals.
- Herdr absence or version/capability mismatch returns an actionable error or configured fallback without losing the queued task.
- Unit tests use a fake Herdr command boundary; opt-in integration tests skip cleanly when herdr is unavailable.
- Provider subscription credentials remain owned by the local Codex/Claude CLI environment, not copied into Clawq records.